A Binance Model Context Protocol (MCP) server is a bridge that allows AI assistants like Claude, Cursor, or ChatGPT to interact directly with the Binance exchange [1][2][3]. These servers enable users to execute trades, access market data, monitor portfolios, and manage accounts through natural language [1][2][4].

There are multiple open-source implementations available, such as those by nirholas, yassais, and others, which vary in scope from a focused set of trading tools to comprehensive support covering nearly 500 Binance API endpoints [2][5][4][6]. To use one, you typically configure your MCP client (like Claude Desktop) with your Binance API keys and secret via your MCP settings file [1][6]. 

Example configuration:
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "binance": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["binance-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "BINANCE_API_KEY": "your_api_key",
        "BINANCE_API_SECRET": "your_api_secret",
        "BINANCE_TESTNET": "false"
      }
    }
  }
}
```
As shown in the example above, you must define the execution command and provide your credentials as environment variables [6]. Most implementations support both mainnet and testnet environments [1][4][6].
